{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Nd9ACF9oHbGWvzji4jQtqe","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the issue. The Prometheus ConfigMap only has a scrape config for itself (`localhost:9090`), but it doesn't have any config to scrape RabbitMQ metrics.\n\nI need to add a scrape config that targets all 3 RabbitMQ pods on port 15692. The best approach is to use the headless service to scrape all 3 pods individually, or use the individual pod IPs. \n\nLooking at the services:\n- `rabbitmq` - ClusterIP service on ports 5672, 15672, 15692\n- `rabbitmq-headless` - Headless service (None ClusterIP) on ports 5672, 15672, 15692\n\nFor Prometheus to scrape all 3 pods individually, I could use static configs with the pod IPs, DNS-based discovery via the headless service, or Kubernetes service discovery. Since there's no restriction on Kubernetes API access, I could use `kubernetes_sd_configs`, though that would require setting up proper RBAC with a ClusterRole and ServiceAccount.\n\nThe simplest approach is using static configs with the headless service DNS names for each pod individually—`rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.NAMESPACE.svc.cluster.local:15692` and so on for all three replicas. This works cleanly since we know exactly how many pods we're dealing with. Now let me look at how Prometheus itself is configured.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":433,"cache_read_input_tokens":29517,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":433},"output_tokens":12,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bdde686e-c90e-478f-8d2d-1b8df40306b1","uuid":"b37c5a3f-e530-43fc-8b70-49d8842b9477","request_id":"req_011CcdpCXJ2PKjsDfDKoyio6"}
